shing engagement in U.S. political life, the practice of dual citizenship by Mexican migrants actually provides a sense of empowerment that fosters migrants' active civic engagement in American as well as Mexican politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenshipzMexico. 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aMexican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspectszMexico. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aLatino/A Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science.1 aBakker, Matt, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146187340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801461873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801461873/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles